node.text:
Tap and rotate your phone for full screen // Photography is my main creative outlet and I love to share my work and some bts on this platform, but what I don’t show much of is the time spent behind a computer editing countless photographs and bringing those RAW files to life in a way that speaks to me. Editing plays such a huge role in one’s style and there are so many different ways to approach it depending on how you view the world around you. Everyone has a unique vision and that’s the beauty of it; creativity can be found anywhere by anyone and with the right tools and sense of imagination, the possibilities are endless of what you can create.

Grateful for @captureonepro for the opportunity to be on the other side of the camera to share a bit of my process. #captureone #sponsored 🎥: @chrisclarkcinema / @kalumko

node.text:
A handful of moments and behind the scene images from our documentary shoot in the Muskawa-Kechika shot on 35mm film. 

This was the first documentary that I’ve ever been a part of, it was a great learning experience and made me want to dive more into this kind of work. Excited to share more closer to the release! @muskwa.film 👈🏻 for more info. 

Some quick tidbits about the M-K Management Area:

➡️The management area is approximately the size of Ireland / twice the size of Vancouver Island (6.4 million hectares).

➡️Nicknamed the “Serengeti of the North” for its abundance of wildlife.

➡️One the largest and most biodiverse areas in the Rocky Mountain range.

➡️The M-KMA includes Parks and Protected Areas where resource extraction is prohibited, and management zones where resource extraction may occur but with higher standards than elsewhere in the province.

➡️The M-KMA lies in the traditional territories of the Kaska Dena, Treaty 8 and Carrier-Sekani.

➡️ Pronounced (musk-quah-ke-chee-kah)

node.text:
Booked this beautiful spot on @hipcamp recently; An off-the-grid yurt tucked away in the forest next to the water with access to a sauna and kayaks, it was the perfect escape to disconnect and recharge.

If you haven’t heard of @hipcamp before, it’s an outdoors focused accommodation booking app — think tent camping, tree houses, cozy cabins, RV parks and more. Their platform opens up a lot of opportunities to stay in unique, private and popular areas, especially with how busy the parks and campgrounds have been this year.

There are some gems on there and they recently expanded into Canada so it’s only going to get better!

Use the code “Taylor25” when making your next booking for 25% off (save this post as a reminder because who doesn’t love a discount?!). 

#HipCampPartner #HipCampCanada #HipCamp

node.text:
I’ve never considered myself a wildlife photographer; I’m more of an opportunist. With that being said, the opportunities while out on the water with @seawolfadventures have been incredibly fruitful over the years. Their guides have a deep connection to the animals and landscapes of the region, and they know exactly where to look and how to read the wildlife to give you the best experience possible. Each visit leaves you with a desire to return and gives you a profound appreciation for Kwakwaka'wakw culture.

If you’re wanting to experience the Great Bear Rainforest for yourself, @Canada is currently running a giveaway for 2 in collaboration with @seawolfadventures. Check out their recent post for a chance to win a once in a lifetime trip! | Sponsored

node.text:
When it comes to visiting the complex network of fjords, inlets and islands on the West Coast of BC, local knowledge and expertise of the land is essential. Over the past few years I’ve been working closely with Mike Willie and his all-time crew at @seawolfadventures to experience and document the Great Bear Rainforest. Mike is a passionate explorer, photographer, storyteller and guide who has immense love for his territory and its inhabitants.

As an Indigenous owned and operated business, Sea Wolf’s tours provide a different depth of experience through sharing their guides Kwakwaka'wakw perspectives and connection to the land—a connection that is thousands of years in the making.
Learning from such knowledgeable folks inspires you to become more invested in the future of the animals, landscapes and cultures of the region & beyond.

Personally, I’ve never gained so much from a tour as I have with @seawolfadventures. I’ve walked away with new perspectives, the most mind-blowing wildlife encounters, and meaningful friendships. I’m honoured to #partner with them this year and deepen our relationship. When you’re planning your next Vancouver Island getaway, be sure to pay them a visit and experience it for yourself!
